            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>ITEM Z103—RABBI SEEKS POSITION, <date>1851</date>. Neatly penned single sheet<lb/>
                letter (blank reverse) 7 ½ x 8. <placeName>New York</placeName>
                <date>August 26, 1851</date> entirely in the<lb/> hand of and signed by “<persName
                    role="author">D. Lilienthall</persName>” to <persName>Rev. Leeser</persName>
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName><lb/> “...allow me to introduce to you
                    <persName>Dr. Zimerman</persName> (sic) a man well instructed<lb/> and who would
                like to get a situation as teacher. If you could help him to<lb/> a place you would
                oblige me very much and I would be very happy if he<lb/> could find a situation like
                that of <persName>Dr. Scwess</persName>, who after having been sometime in
                    <placeName>Phila</placeName><lb/> got such a pleasant situation. Do for him what
                you can, he is without nay means<lb/> whatever.” Lightest aging. Exc. Small tatters
                on the extreme edge of bottom blank margin<lb/> only. Reverse acts as cover with
                address to <persName>Leeser</persName>...</p>
            <p rend="align(center)">______________________</p>
            <p>2 of 13</p>
            <p rend="align(right)"><date>1<lb/>15<lb/>02</date> 8:07 PM</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>New York</placeName>
                <date>Aug 26. 51</date>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sir!</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Allow me to introduce to you <persName>Dr<lb/>
                    Zim<add>m</add>erman</persName>, a man, well instructed and who would<lb/> like
                to get a situation as teacher. If you could help<lb/> him to a place, you would
                oblige me very much; and<lb/> I would be very happy, if he could find a
                situation<lb/> like that of <persName>Dr. Lehwess<add>?</add></persName>, who after
                having been some„<lb/>time in <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>, got such a
                pleasant situation.<lb/> Do for him, what you can, as he is without any<lb/> means
                whatever and oblige Yours truly</p>
            <p rend="indent(6)">
                <persName role="author">D. Lilienthal</persName>
            </p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Rev. I. Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
            </p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p rend="indent(3)">
                <addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">
